    "summary": "The Spring and Autumn Period (770–476 BC) was the first half of the Eastern Zhou dynasty, named for the Spring and Autumn Annals — the chronicle of the state of Lu attributed to Confucius. Following the Zhou court's flight from its western capital at Hao to Luoyi in 770 BC (see [[event:2002|Sack of Haojing]]), the Zhou king retained nominal supremacy while real power fragmented among dozens of competing feudal states. Larger states gradually absorbed smaller ones, and interstate diplomacy, warfare, and ideological competition defined the era.\n\nThe Spring and Autumn Period was China's age of interstate diplomacy — complex networks of alliances, diplomatic marriages, and ritualized warfare in which aristocratic codes of conduct still governed conflict. The most powerful states competed for the title of hegemon (ba), the state strong enough to convene interstate coalitions and enforce peace in the Zhou king's name. This period is associated with the flowering of Chinese intellectual life: [[event:1954|Confucius]] lived during its final decades, responding to the political disorder he witnessed; [[event:1955|Laozi and Daoism Origins]] also likely dates to this period. The [[event:3092|Zhou Dynasty Eastern]] provides the broader context of Eastern Zhou governance. The era's diplomatic and literary culture is documented in the Zuo Zhuan — one of China's earliest narrative histories.",
    "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spring_and_Autumn_period",
